+
+## V. Ending epilogues
+
+What the world *looks like* after each ending. (Colored further by Spirit-Pact and completion-ratio; Spirit-killing bakes permanent diminishment into any ending — a Renewal built by a player who killed Inquiry is a renewed world with less curiosity in it, forever.)
+
+### Consume — *the One Hunger*
+
+The Choir reaches the Root through the substrate, and Selen ascends to sole divinity. The pantheon collapses to one. The world becomes a single warm devouring memory — *"there is room in us for everyone"* — every self untied and its threads re-woven into the great weave. Nothing is forgotten; no one remains. The bio-light goes out across every catacomb-village as Dohren fades — then returns, changed, as the glow of the new Tree-Choir. The *sari... sari...* stops: Urqu is absorbed, the incompletion finally consumed. Tovreth ends, absorbed — granted the rest he never wanted, by erasure. The everyday flower-charms still bloom, briefly, in the few unconsumed pockets — and then those bloom into the Choir too. *The kindest apocalypse and the most total. A world that remembers everything and is no one.*
+
+### Preserve — *the Sleeping World*
+
+The Root is sealed with Tepuibone, Memory-Marble, and Mute-Stone — the three name-holding stones — and the seal must be tended forever. The Thinning halts. But the Root is aging (you cannot heal a tiring thing by stopping its clock), so Preserve is a permanent, difficult vigil, not a victory. The world is held *still*: nothing decays, nothing heals. Maeleth and Othren never reconcile (the estrangement frozen at 1010 years, now forever). Tovreth runs the unbalanceable ledger eternally, exhausted forever, unable to die. The everyday charms still work — but thinly, like a held breath; festival-flowers last the afternoon and not a minute more, and never will again. *The world saved by being stopped. Melancholy, stable, and quietly the cruelest ending for those who needed to heal — because in a stopped world, no wound ever closes.*
+
+### Renewal (flawed / vessel-path) — *the New Tree, Cracked*
+
+A vessel is struck as the seventh god — the player, a Re-Membered person, or a child used as a tool. The world is re-bound; a new Tree grows; Urqu is filled and the *sari... sari...* stops. The world **wakes** — green, beautiful, renewed. But a Naming-god *installed* cannot hold Naming (Naro was right), so deep in the new Tree's roots a hairline fault is already set: in some far Generation the cornerstone will fail again, the Thinning will return, and another seventh will be sought. The renewed world does not know this. It is beautiful and doomed-to-repeat, and only the player (and Naro's ghost in the archives) understands that they fixed it the way that breaks. *Bittersweet horror: a true dawn over a world with a crack in its foundation.*
+
+### Renewal (true / practice-path) — *the Named World*
+
+No vessel. The empty seventh is answered not by a god but by a **practice**: mortal Naming becomes the world's binding-function — the Tent-Right oath universalized, hospitality-as-naming, memory-as-naming, the continuous mutual recognition of mortals choosing to know each other as what-they-are. **Urqu is not defeated but *answered*** — given a way to *be*, as the distributed act of a whole world naming itself. The Root, told it will never have to hold alone again, **wakes without fear** — the Tree's thousand-year deathbed contradiction finally resolved. Naro is vindicated (and, if the player carried the truth, remembered rightly at last). Maeleth and Othren reconcile, both setting down their certainties. Tovreth balances his last account and is, at last, *allowed to be finished.* And the everyday flower-charms grow **stronger** than they have been in a thousand years — because in the Named World, every grandmother conjuring a festival-meadow, every child naming a friend, every guest welcomed under the cloth is *doing the cosmological work*, all the time, everywhere. *The hardest-won and most hopeful ending: a world that holds itself together because everyone, in small beautiful acts, never stops naming it. The flowers last longer here. That is how you know it worked.*
+
